Well, here's the rub. There are certain specifics to copyright law regarding
music. Once a song is published, anyone else can do a cover version provided
they pay the appropriate royalties established by statute and fill out the
right forms. It's called a mechanical license, and it's such a routine
process you can do it over the web. The copyright holder can't stop someone
from doing a cover. See www.harryfox.com for details.

However, the copyright holder of a song has the exclusive right to first
publication. That means that if you write a song, nobody else can release a
cover version of that song until you've released your version. I think it is
safe to say that once you post on the Internet, that counts as being
published.

There are worse things that could happen to you than some record company
blowing off your band and having their preferred band cover your song.
You'll make the statutory royalty (currently 9.1 cents per copy I believe).

Another potential issue is illustrated by &quot;Mr. Tambourine Man&quot; by Bob Dylan.
A live version was recorded at a music festival. He didn't like that
version. His record company wanted to release it, and he pretty much had no
control over what they released. However, since that song had never been
released before, he was able to deny his own record company a mechanical
license.

Personally, I think the benefits clearly outweigh the potential problems
with putting up your music before your band is signed. However, if I were
ever in a situation where my band was in contract discussions/negotiations
with a record label, I would not post anything new unless I absolutely had
to. No sense relinquishing any rights you don't have to.

On a side note: That mailing yourself a letter stuff is something lawyers
like to laugh about. First, there's no guarantee that your stamp will get
canceled with a date. Second, even WikiHow tells you how to steam open an
envelope ( http://www.wikihow.com/Steam-Open-an-Envelope ). You think a judge
or jury would give your letter any weight?
